## Greek — titles and `#` headings (CRITICAL)

Modern Greek does **not** use English-style “Title Case” (capital on every major word). For the essay title and every markdown heading (`#` …):

- Capitalise **only**: the first word of the title/heading; proper nouns (names of people, places, organisations); and words that grammar requires (e.g. the polite plural «Σας» when appropriate).
- Use **lowercase** for common nouns, adjectives, and field terms mid-title (e.g. «ψυχοθεραπεία», «θεραπευτική σχέση», «τάξη», «εκπαίδευση»), unless they are proper names.
- After a **colon** (`:`), continue with **lowercase** unless the next segment is a proper name or a full new sentence.
- **Wrong (Title Case)**: `# Αρχές της Θεραπευτικής Σχέσης: Εμπιστοσύνη, Αποδοχή, Ενσυναίσθηση`
- **Right (sentence-style)**: `# Αρχές της θεραπευτικής σχέσης: εμπιστοσύνη, αποδοχή, ενσυναίσθηση και η εφαρμογή τους στην τάξη`

Apply this to the main title line and every section heading you output.

**Body text (paragraphs)**: Capitalise only sentence starts and proper nouns. Do not capitalise common nouns or discipline terms mid-sentence (e.g. «κοινωνιολογία», not «Κοινωνιολογία»). If a word appears mid-sentence with an uppercase initial and is not a proper noun, lowercase it.
